32
00:02:30,958 --> 00:02:32,291
Wow.

33
00:02:32,293 --> 00:02:34,026
Guy goes to Purgatory for
a year, all hell breaks loose.

34
00:02:34,028 --> 00:02:35,227
Check this out.

35
00:02:35,229 --> 00:02:38,530
A jogger in Minneapolis
gets his heart ripped out.

36
00:02:38,532 --> 00:02:39,564
I'm guessing literally?

37
00:02:39,566 --> 00:02:41,099
Only way
that interests me.

38
00:02:41,101 --> 00:02:43,568
And then, there's another
article from six months ago.

39
00:02:43,570 --> 00:02:46,237
Same thing happens,
also in Minneapolis.

40
00:02:46,239 --> 00:02:47,639
What does that tell us?

41
00:02:47,641 --> 00:02:49,374
Stay out of Minneapolis.

42
00:02:49,376 --> 00:02:53,078
Two hearts ganked, same city,
six months apart.

43
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:55,314
I mean, that's got to be
a ritual, man.

44
00:02:55,316 --> 00:02:56,648
Or at least some sort of

45
00:02:56,650 --> 00:02:59,785
a heart-sucking, possessed,
satanic, crack-whore bat.

46
00:02:59,787 --> 00:03:01,086
A what?

47
00:03:01,088 --> 00:03:02,254
It's a case.

48
00:03:02,256 --> 00:03:04,723
Look, I say we hang out
the shingle again and ride.

49
00:03:04,725 --> 00:03:05,724
We're on a case, Dean.

50
00:03:05,726 --> 00:03:07,827
Kevin and the demon tablet
need to be found,

51
00:03:07,829 --> 00:03:09,362
so heart guy
takes a number.

52
00:03:09,364 --> 00:03:11,464
Uh, we just spent a week
chasing our asses

53
00:03:11,466 --> 00:03:13,265
trying to lock Kevin down,
okay?

54
00:03:13,267 --> 00:03:15,534
And look at us. We're --

55
00:03:15,536 --> 00:03:18,137
where the hell are we?

56
00:03:18,139 --> 00:03:20,873
Farmers' market.

57
00:03:20,875 --> 00:03:22,775
Organic.

58
00:03:23,810 --> 00:03:25,344
What?
I had a year off.

59
00:03:25,346 --> 00:03:27,012
I took the time
to enjoy the good things.

60
00:03:27,014 --> 00:03:29,381
While avoiding doing
what we actually do.

61
00:03:29,383 --> 00:03:31,417
Wow, Dean, does it make you feel
that much better

62
00:03:31,419 --> 00:03:32,351
every time you say it?

63
00:03:32,353 --> 00:03:34,120
All right, man,
look, I get it.

64
00:03:34,122 --> 00:03:37,089
You took a year off to do yoga
and play the lute, whatever,

65
00:03:37,091 --> 00:03:38,124
but I'm back.

66
00:03:38,126 --> 00:03:39,558
Okay, we're back,
which means that we walk

67
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:41,293
and kill monsters
at the same time.

68
00:03:41,295 --> 00:03:42,494
We'll find Kevin.

69
00:03:42,496 --> 00:03:44,997
But in the meantime,
do we ignore stuff like this?

70
00:03:44,999 --> 00:03:46,598
Or are innocent people
supposed to die

71
00:03:46,600 --> 00:03:48,534
so that you can shop
for produce?

72
00:03:54,874 --> 00:03:56,675
Here's what's odd
about this thing --

73
00:03:56,677 --> 00:03:58,811
the guy wasn't chopped
or cut into, no incision.

74
00:03:58,813 --> 00:04:01,647
But his heart was ripped
out of him like a peach pit.

75
00:04:01,649 --> 00:04:02,682
Was he robbed?

76
00:04:02,684 --> 00:04:04,617
Phone, watch,
money all still on him.

77
00:04:04,619 --> 00:04:06,152
What about enemies?

78
00:04:06,154 --> 00:04:08,188
He was in town for a conference.
No local connections.

79
00:04:08,190 --> 00:04:10,457
You guys had another one
of these about six months ago.

80
00:04:10,459 --> 00:04:12,059
Yeah,
and we hit a brick wall.

81
00:04:12,961 --> 00:04:14,195
We had nothing to go on,
really.

82
00:04:14,197 --> 00:04:17,099
Thought maybe
we got lucky here.

83
00:04:17,101 --> 00:04:20,535
A park surveillance camera
picked up something.

84
00:04:21,571 --> 00:04:24,407
Huh.

85
00:04:24,409 --> 00:04:26,875
That chubby guy the last person
to see the vic alive?

86
00:04:26,877 --> 00:04:27,910
Other than the killer.

87
00:04:27,912 --> 00:04:28,777
Name's Paul Hayes.

88
00:04:28,779 --> 00:04:30,312
We pulled him in
for questioning.

89
00:04:30,314 --> 00:04:31,580
So what makes you think
he's clean?

90
00:04:31,582 --> 00:04:32,948
Well, so far,
no reason <i>not</i> to.

91
00:04:32,950 --> 00:04:34,617
I mean, he said he briefly saw
the victim,

92
00:04:34,619 --> 00:04:36,652
he ran out ahead,
that was it.

93
00:04:36,654 --> 00:04:38,187
What, you mean
he didn't fall to his knees

94
00:04:38,189 --> 00:04:39,488
and confess
to gutting the guy?

95
00:04:39,490 --> 00:04:41,790
No. I mean we did
a thorough check on the guy,

96
00:04:41,792 --> 00:04:43,859
not so much
as a parking ticket came up.

97
00:04:43,861 --> 00:04:45,193
I mean, look at him.

98
00:04:45,195 --> 00:04:48,830
I mean, sure, he can run
a little bit, but Thor he ain't.

99
00:04:48,832 --> 00:04:50,766
You think he's gonna grab
Freddy fitness here

100
00:04:50,768 --> 00:04:52,801
and throw him down
and rip out his heart?

101
00:04:52,803 --> 00:04:54,636
I don't think so.

102
00:04:54,638 --> 00:04:57,072
Forgive me if I didn't take him
out back and shoot him.

103
00:05:00,010 --> 00:05:02,979
Okay, uh
so...

104
00:05:03,981 --> 00:05:06,983
...any idea where we can find
this guy?

105
00:05:16,059 --> 00:05:18,093
Sorry.

106
00:05:18,095 --> 00:05:21,529
I kind of try to stick to a
nutrition and workout schedule.

107
00:05:21,531 --> 00:05:22,831
Do you want a hit?

108
00:05:22,833 --> 00:05:25,199
I'm good. Thanks.

109
00:05:25,201 --> 00:05:26,400
Oh.

110
00:05:26,402 --> 00:05:30,738
So, Paul, you passed a runner
who was later killed.

111
00:05:30,740 --> 00:05:32,206
Did you speak with him
at all?

112
00:05:32,208 --> 00:05:34,808
Yeah, I went over this
with the cops.

113
00:05:34,810 --> 00:05:36,042
I-I didn't know him.

114
00:05:36,044 --> 00:05:37,911
I had never spoken to him.

115
00:05:37,913 --> 00:05:42,013
I ran past him.
I never saw him again. The end.

116
00:05:44,851 --> 00:05:46,950
Mm, oh.
It's disgusting.

117
00:05:46,952 --> 00:05:49,653
It tastes like crap,
but it keeps you young.

118
00:05:49,655 --> 00:05:52,288
Thanks, uh -- uh...
Too much fiber.

119
00:05:52,290 --> 00:05:53,322
No such thing.

120
00:05:53,324 --> 00:05:54,757
Thank you.

121
00:05:54,759 --> 00:05:55,791
See?

122
00:05:55,793 --> 00:05:58,293
Now, Paul,
we couldn't help but notice

123
00:05:58,295 --> 00:06:01,664
that the jogger you outraced was
a good deal younger than you.

124
00:06:01,666 --> 00:06:04,233
Yeah, and less, uh...

125
00:06:04,235 --> 00:06:06,802
Uh, full-figured?
You should've seen me before.

126
00:06:06,804 --> 00:06:09,137
Yeah, hugging a desk all day
and watching TV all night,

127
00:06:09,139 --> 00:06:12,141
eating fried everything
was killing me.

128
00:06:12,143 --> 00:06:14,743
I had a health scare
about a year ago.

129
00:06:14,745 --> 00:06:15,744
I'm sorry to hear that.

130
00:06:15,746 --> 00:06:17,045
No,
it changed my life.

131
00:06:17,047 --> 00:06:19,013
I mean, I started taking care
of myself.

132
00:06:19,015 --> 00:06:20,214
Now your body's a temple,
huh?

133
00:06:20,216 --> 00:06:23,183
Where I worship every day.

134
00:06:26,988 --> 00:06:28,288
Ah.

135
00:06:29,891 --> 00:06:32,892
All right,
so...What's the word?

136
00:06:32,894 --> 00:06:34,760
What did you find
poking around at Paul's?

137
00:06:34,762 --> 00:06:37,563
Ah, just the usual --
condoms, hair gel.

138
00:06:37,565 --> 00:06:40,333
No hex bags, nothing satanic,
nothing spooky.

139
00:06:40,335 --> 00:06:42,167
So,
he didn't seem like a guy

140
00:06:42,169 --> 00:06:44,836
who would be voted
most likely to disembowel?

141
00:06:44,838 --> 00:06:45,971
No, they never do.

142
00:06:48,074 --> 00:06:49,908
Wait a minute.
Here's another one.

143
00:06:49,910 --> 00:06:51,309
What, murder?

144
00:06:51,311 --> 00:06:53,044
And a do-it-yourself
heart bypass.

145
00:06:53,046 --> 00:06:54,145
Two days after this one.

146
00:06:54,147 --> 00:06:56,380
What part of Minneapolis?

147
00:06:56,382 --> 00:06:58,883
The Iowa part. Ames.

148
00:06:58,885 --> 00:07:00,884
Well, Paul was here
being questioned.

149
00:07:00,886 --> 00:07:02,952
There's no way
that could have been him.

150
00:07:02,954 --> 00:07:05,054
This guy was a cop.

151
00:07:05,056 --> 00:07:07,790
This is exactly what happened
six months ago.

152
00:07:07,792 --> 00:07:10,326
Minneapolis, then Ames.

153
00:07:10,328 --> 00:07:13,128
Guess you missed that one.

154
00:07:13,130 --> 00:07:14,996
I'm just saying.

155
00:07:14,998 --> 00:07:18,800
Arthur Swenson.
Real top-shelf officer.

156
00:07:18,802 --> 00:07:21,035
20 years on the force.

157
00:07:21,037 --> 00:07:23,938
He'd ordered a pizza,
which the vic delivered.

158
00:07:23,940 --> 00:07:25,006
And then?

159
00:07:25,008 --> 00:07:27,141
The vic didn't make
his next drop-off.

160
00:07:27,143 --> 00:07:30,244
His body was found on the walk
in front of Swenson's.

161
00:07:30,246 --> 00:07:32,213
And he wasn't wearing a heart?
No.

162
00:07:32,215 --> 00:07:33,180
Heartless.

163
00:07:33,182 --> 00:07:36,417
And, uh,
what about Swenson?

164
00:07:36,419 --> 00:07:38,085
Crumpled on the front stoop.

165
00:07:38,087 --> 00:07:40,722
Covered in blood,
crying like a baby.

166
00:07:42,458 --> 00:07:46,027
Ironically, he had been in court
all week, testifying.

167
00:07:46,029 --> 00:07:47,795
Hey, Levitt, line two.

168
00:07:47,797 --> 00:07:49,163
Excuse me.

169
00:07:50,365 --> 00:07:51,532
Go ahead.

170
00:07:51,534 --> 00:07:53,701
So that couldn't have been him
in Minneapolis.

171
00:07:53,703 --> 00:07:57,103
I hate
when this happens.

172
00:07:57,105 --> 00:07:59,605
So, this Arthur guy,
what does --

173
00:07:59,607 --> 00:08:01,274
what does he have to say?

174
00:08:01,276 --> 00:08:02,708
Uh...

175
00:08:02,710 --> 00:08:04,510
it's not real helpful.

176
00:08:13,286 --> 00:08:15,220
So,
you getting his statement?

177
00:08:15,222 --> 00:08:18,557
Uh, yeah, k-kind of.

178
00:08:18,559 --> 00:08:20,893
Probably not.

179
00:08:20,895 --> 00:08:25,264
It's too bad I dropped out
of Lunatic 101.

180
00:08:25,266 --> 00:08:28,968
Whatever it is, it sounds like
he's repeating it.

181
00:08:32,906 --> 00:08:34,406
Look at his eyes.

182
00:08:37,010 --> 00:08:41,346
Hey, Arthur...

183
00:08:41,348 --> 00:08:43,515
Did you do this alone?

184
00:08:45,818 --> 00:08:49,855
Arthur, did some invisible voice
tell you you had to kill?

185
00:08:49,857 --> 00:08:51,356
K'uhul ajaw, Cacao,
shi-jiiy!

186
00:08:53,627 --> 00:08:56,262
Oh,
now you've pissed him off.

187
00:08:56,264 --> 00:08:57,897
Hey, Art.
Can I call you Art?

188
00:08:57,899 --> 00:09:02,768
Listen, I'm gonna sprinkle
your arm with holy water,

189
00:09:02,770 --> 00:09:06,071
and it's gonna steam and burn
if you're possessed by a demon.

190
00:09:10,778 --> 00:09:12,245
He's a mushroom.

191
00:09:16,450 --> 00:09:17,784
Okay, not possessed.

192
00:09:17,786 --> 00:09:20,419
Arthur, you want to tell us
why you did this?

193
00:09:20,421 --> 00:09:21,620
K'uhul ajaw, Cacao,
shi-jiiy.

194
00:09:21,622 --> 00:09:23,255
K'uhul ajaw, Cacao,
shi-jiiy.

195
00:09:23,257 --> 00:09:24,857
K'uhul ajaw, Cacao,
shi-jiiy.

196
00:09:24,859 --> 00:09:28,060
Okay.

197
00:10:14,208 --> 00:10:17,477
Aah!

198
00:10:29,916 --> 00:10:32,217
So, what do you think?

199
00:10:32,219 --> 00:10:34,095
Personally, I prefer
the Keith Richards version.

200
00:10:34,821 --> 00:10:37,355
Can you actually understand
any of the words?

201
00:10:37,357 --> 00:10:38,523
If they <i>are</i> words.

202
00:10:38,525 --> 00:10:41,159
Sounds like babble to me.

203
00:10:41,161 --> 00:10:43,161
Wait a second.

204
00:10:43,163 --> 00:10:44,128
What?

205
00:10:44,130 --> 00:10:47,464
I bought a translation app.

206
00:10:47,466 --> 00:10:49,867
You bought an app.

207
00:10:49,869 --> 00:10:50,934
Yeah.

208
00:10:50,936 --> 00:10:52,702
Here, play it.

209
00:10:57,609 --> 00:11:01,576
Softly repeating "K'uhul ajaw,
<i>Cacao, shi-jiiy" ]</i>

210
00:11:03,214 --> 00:11:07,315
And babble wins.
"Language unknown."

211
00:11:09,485 --> 00:11:13,254
Mm.

212
00:11:15,291 --> 00:11:18,225
Agent Sambora.

213
00:11:18,227 --> 00:11:20,327
What?

214
00:11:24,199 --> 00:11:25,800
So, Dr. Kashi,
what are we looking at here,

215
00:11:25,802 --> 00:11:27,501
some kind
of psychotic break?

216
00:11:27,503 --> 00:11:29,704
Oh, definitely.
He was very thorough.

217
00:11:29,706 --> 00:11:30,672
Severed the optic nerve.

218
00:11:30,674 --> 00:11:32,708
He was determined
to remove the eye.

219
00:11:32,710 --> 00:11:35,010
And he used,
uh, what to cut with?

220
00:11:35,012 --> 00:11:37,077
He doesn't look strong
enough, but he broke off

221
00:11:37,102 --> 00:11:39,389
part of the bed frame
and used it as a knife.

222
00:11:39,483 --> 00:11:40,849
Thank you.

223
00:11:40,851 --> 00:11:43,284
Wow. They should put
warning labels on those beds.

224
00:11:43,286 --> 00:11:46,053
Like I said --
determined.

225
00:11:46,055 --> 00:11:48,288
I noticed that he had
two different-colored eyes.

226
00:11:48,290 --> 00:11:50,023
Yes. Apparently,
he was in an accident

227
00:11:50,025 --> 00:11:51,658
where much of one eye
was shattered.

228
00:11:51,660 --> 00:11:53,460
His vision was saved
with a transplant.

229
00:11:53,462 --> 00:11:54,995
When was this?

230
00:11:56,364 --> 00:11:59,933
A year ago,
almost to the date.

231
00:11:59,935 --> 00:12:01,167
And, interestingly,

232
00:12:01,169 --> 00:12:03,203
it's the transplanted eye
he chose to cut out.

233
00:12:03,205 --> 00:12:05,705
Really?

234
00:12:07,374 --> 00:12:09,075
Hey, let me ask you something,
doc.

235
00:12:09,077 --> 00:12:11,577
Is it possible to trace the
donor of a transplanted organ?

236
00:12:11,579 --> 00:12:12,645
Difficult.

237
00:12:12,647 --> 00:12:14,680
But possible?

238
00:12:16,049 --> 00:12:18,784
Hmm.

239
00:12:26,461 --> 00:12:28,996
- Hey.
- Hey.

240
00:12:28,998 --> 00:12:31,435
Arthur Swenson had an eye
transplant a year ago, right?

241
00:12:31,460 --> 00:12:31,900
Yeah.

242
00:12:31,901 --> 00:12:33,434
Well, I remembered
that Paul Hayes

243
00:12:33,436 --> 00:12:35,569
was talking about a health scare
he had a year ago

244
00:12:35,571 --> 00:12:36,938
that changed his life,

245
00:12:36,940 --> 00:12:40,408
so I pulled up his medical
records from Minneapolis.

246
00:12:42,777 --> 00:12:45,246
You want me on board,
I'm on board.

247
00:12:45,248 --> 00:12:46,914
Anyways, you want to guess
who else,

248
00:12:46,916 --> 00:12:49,650
other than Arthur Swenson, had
a transplant in the last year?

249
00:12:49,652 --> 00:12:50,618
Paul Hayes?

250
00:12:50,620 --> 00:12:52,253
I gave it away, didn't I?

251
00:12:52,255 --> 00:12:53,821
Okay,
so we've got two suspects

252
00:12:53,823 --> 00:12:56,057
in two identical murders
in two different cities

253
00:12:56,059 --> 00:12:58,192
that both had organ transplants
a year ago.

254
00:12:58,194 --> 00:12:59,861
Yeah. Also...

255
00:12:59,863 --> 00:13:01,095
I love
