508
00:26:41,250 --> 00:26:44,050
Yeah. "Love, me."

509
00:26:44,052 --> 00:26:46,286
Here. "Dearest Betsy,
on the road again.

510
00:26:46,288 --> 00:26:48,155
"So hard to be away from you,
honey.

511
00:26:48,157 --> 00:26:49,743
Will give the Red Sox hell

512
00:26:49,768 --> 00:26:51,393
and get back to you."
"Dearest Betsy..."

513
00:26:51,394 --> 00:26:53,628
"Dearest Betsy, Le Mans will be
a bitch this year with all the rain..."

514
00:26:53,630 --> 00:26:55,430
"...the Phillies are tough,
but we're looking to be tougher..."

515
00:26:55,432 --> 00:26:57,398
"...them Dodgers will wish
they never left Brooklyn..."

516
00:26:57,400 --> 00:26:59,234
"...looking for my best gal
Friday night at the Garden..."

517
00:26:59,236 --> 00:27:01,035
"...our o-line hung tough.
I had all day back there..."

518
00:27:01,037 --> 00:27:03,404
"...Alain Prost is a monster
in the straightaway..."

519
00:27:03,406 --> 00:27:04,772
"Dearest Betsy..."
"Dearest Betsy..."

520
00:27:04,774 --> 00:27:05,873
"Love, me."

521
00:27:05,875 --> 00:27:08,442
Wait,
this one looks recent.

522
00:27:08,444 --> 00:27:11,077
"Dearest Betsy...

523
00:27:11,079 --> 00:27:12,412
So tired of it all."

524
00:27:19,653 --> 00:27:20,954
Hey.

525
00:27:20,956 --> 00:27:24,057
I pulled up the names
on those trophies. Check it out.

526
00:27:26,795 --> 00:27:29,230
All right, Brick Holmes --
football player.

527
00:27:29,232 --> 00:27:30,832
Charlie Karnes --
race-car driver.

528
00:27:30,834 --> 00:27:32,701
Davey Samuelson --
baseball player.

529
00:27:32,703 --> 00:27:33,669
Kelly Duran -- boxer.

530
00:27:33,671 --> 00:27:35,804
Four different guys, right?
Okay.

531
00:27:35,806 --> 00:27:37,673
Check this out.

532
00:27:41,746 --> 00:27:44,680
Same dark eyes, same cheekbones,
nose, mouth.

533
00:27:44,682 --> 00:27:47,282
Wait, are you saying
that these four guys

534
00:27:47,284 --> 00:27:48,984
who all look to be
in their mid-20s

535
00:27:48,986 --> 00:27:52,187
and go back 70 years
could be the same guy?

536
00:27:52,189 --> 00:27:55,290
Wow.

537
00:27:55,292 --> 00:27:58,194
For a 95-year-old,
Brick Holmes could take a hit.

538
00:28:06,248 --> 00:28:09,016
So, if all those athletes
were the same guy,

539
00:28:09,018 --> 00:28:10,719
how'd he pull it off?

540
00:28:10,721 --> 00:28:14,823
Appear, then go away
and come back with a new look?

541
00:28:14,825 --> 00:28:16,592
Cacao, the, uh, the --
the maize God --

542
00:28:16,594 --> 00:28:18,560
was Mayan, right?
Yeah.

543
00:28:18,562 --> 00:28:20,996
The Maya were all about war
and torture and conquest...

544
00:28:20,998 --> 00:28:22,630
and sports.

545
00:28:22,632 --> 00:28:24,732
It says, "Their athletes
were treated like kings.

546
00:28:24,734 --> 00:28:27,434
"The Mayan jocks made sacrifices
to Cacao by --"

547
00:28:27,436 --> 00:28:28,836
ready for this? --

548
00:28:28,838 --> 00:28:31,571
"killing a victim, pulling out
his heart, and eating it."

549
00:28:31,573 --> 00:28:35,075
They believed the rituals
gave them super-charged power

550
00:28:35,077 --> 00:28:37,777
over their opponents.

551
00:28:37,779 --> 00:28:39,846
Yeah, but they didn't stay young
forever.

552
00:28:39,848 --> 00:28:41,347
So, what?

553
00:28:41,349 --> 00:28:44,284
Maybe Brick just made some kind
of deal with this Cacao?

554
00:28:44,286 --> 00:28:45,952
Well,
we've seen it before --

555
00:28:45,954 --> 00:28:47,754
people making deals
with demons, Gods.

556
00:28:47,756 --> 00:28:49,622
I mean, maybe he stayed
young and strong

557
00:28:49,624 --> 00:28:51,458
so long as his sacrifices
kept coming.

558
00:28:51,460 --> 00:28:54,160
Remember all that antique
sports equipment he had?

559
00:28:54,162 --> 00:28:56,363
This guy could go back
to the Mayan days.

560
00:28:56,365 --> 00:28:57,531
Wow.

561
00:28:57,533 --> 00:29:02,669
So, one of the greatest QBs
to ever play the game

562
00:29:02,671 --> 00:29:04,271
was over 900 years old.

563
00:29:04,273 --> 00:29:05,805
Well,
that explains Brick,

564
00:29:05,807 --> 00:29:08,241
but what about the mooks
carrying his spare parts?

565
00:29:08,243 --> 00:29:10,243
Maybe the spell
went along for the ride

566
00:29:10,245 --> 00:29:12,445
and infected the people
who got his organs.

567
00:29:12,447 --> 00:29:14,480
Remember how Paul Hayes said

568
00:29:14,482 --> 00:29:16,783
he had a health scare
that changed his life?

569
00:29:16,785 --> 00:29:18,551
I mean, maybe the spell
could compel him

570
00:29:18,553 --> 00:29:20,019
to keep carrying out
the ritual.

571
00:29:20,021 --> 00:29:21,654
Sort of like getting bit
by a werewolf.

572
00:29:21,656 --> 00:29:23,923
I mean, once you're infected,
you do what you got to do,

573
00:29:23,925 --> 00:29:25,491
especially if you like
the results.

574
00:29:25,493 --> 00:29:28,094
Right, except old Arthur,
the dedicated cop,

575
00:29:28,096 --> 00:29:30,096
couldn't handle it
and went nuts.

576
00:29:33,669 --> 00:29:36,736
Brick Holmes, a heart eater.
Who knew?

577
00:29:36,738 --> 00:29:38,204
Hey, sorry, buddy.

578
00:29:38,206 --> 00:29:43,209
The mighty --
they fall hard, huh?

579
00:29:43,211 --> 00:29:46,111
Well, at least he wasn't
sleeping with his mother.

580
00:29:46,113 --> 00:29:48,714
Yeah, good, Sam.
Find the silver lining.

581
00:29:48,716 --> 00:29:51,150
No, seriously. Look.

582
00:29:57,223 --> 00:29:59,124
"Fighter Kelly Duran
is congratulated

583
00:29:59,126 --> 00:30:02,227
on a second-round knockout
by wife Betsy."

584
00:30:02,229 --> 00:30:05,062
"Dearest Betsy."

585
00:30:10,302 --> 00:30:11,335
Hello, Eleanor.

586
00:30:11,337 --> 00:30:14,906
Or would you rather us
call you Betsy?

587
00:30:16,308 --> 00:30:18,677
Look, Eleanor,
innocent people are dying.

588
00:30:18,679 --> 00:30:22,180
And they're gonna continue
to die until we stop it.

589
00:30:24,150 --> 00:30:26,585
Did you know about the murders
over the past year?

590
00:30:29,089 --> 00:30:31,424
No. I didn't.
I swear.

591
00:30:31,426 --> 00:30:35,929
I thought when -- when
Brick died, it would be over.

592
00:30:35,931 --> 00:30:37,397
Help us.

593
00:30:37,399 --> 00:30:41,201
Betsy, this is not what you want
Brick's legacy to be.

594
00:30:44,472 --> 00:30:49,410
His Mayan name was Inyo.

595
00:30:49,412 --> 00:30:56,150
He was a proud young athlete
nearly 1,000 years ago.

596
00:30:56,152 --> 00:30:57,784
He lived for sport

597
00:30:57,786 --> 00:31:00,787
and never wanted
his days in the sun to end.

598
00:31:00,789 --> 00:31:05,925
So he arranged a bargain
with the God Cacao

599
00:31:05,927 --> 00:31:07,126
through a high priest.

600
00:31:07,128 --> 00:31:08,460
Stay young forever.

601
00:31:08,462 --> 00:31:12,431
As long as the sacrifices
continued, twice a year --

602
00:31:12,433 --> 00:31:15,667
once for the planting,
once for harvest.

603
00:31:15,669 --> 00:31:17,636
When did you find out
about this?

604
00:31:17,638 --> 00:31:21,606
Not until I began to age
and -- and Brick --

605
00:31:21,608 --> 00:31:26,578
Kelly, as he was
when I met him -- did not.

606
00:31:26,580 --> 00:31:31,751
But by that time, Brick himself
had changed...inside.

607
00:31:31,753 --> 00:31:34,219
He wasn't just the warrior

608
00:31:34,221 --> 00:31:36,555
whose only reason for living
was combat.

609
00:31:36,557 --> 00:31:37,956
He --

610
00:31:37,958 --> 00:31:42,194
we were deeply,
deeply in love.

611
00:31:42,196 --> 00:31:46,965
So in love, I'm ashamed to say,
that when I found out that --

612
00:31:46,967 --> 00:31:49,534
how my husband stayed
young and strong,

613
00:31:49,536 --> 00:31:51,403
I chose to ignore it.

614
00:31:51,405 --> 00:31:53,605
You and Brick had to go
underground from time to time

615
00:31:53,607 --> 00:31:55,073
to hide your secret, right?

616
00:31:55,075 --> 00:31:56,508
Every 10 years or so,

617
00:31:56,510 --> 00:32:00,813
he would re-emerge
with a new look, a new name.

618
00:32:00,815 --> 00:32:04,483
And me, I was the wife,

619
00:32:04,485 --> 00:32:07,619
and I was the woman
in hiding,

620
00:32:07,621 --> 00:32:11,189
and then,
when I got into my 40s,

621
00:32:11,191 --> 00:32:15,661
I became Brick's mother.

622
00:32:15,663 --> 00:32:18,196
Eleanor.

623
00:32:20,767 --> 00:32:24,002
I am so tired.

624
00:32:24,004 --> 00:32:26,939
You can't imagine
the burden of it all.

625
00:32:26,941 --> 00:32:29,741
I think even Brick
was through.

626
00:32:29,743 --> 00:32:33,746
He could see the end of my days
were at hand, and...

627
00:32:33,748 --> 00:32:38,217
He had lived centuries
all alone,

628
00:32:38,219 --> 00:32:40,386
but I don't think
he could bear the thought

629
00:32:40,388 --> 00:32:41,553
of life without me.

630
00:32:43,723 --> 00:32:46,725
That's why he drove
off that bridge.

631
00:32:52,499 --> 00:32:54,366
You must think
I'm a monster.

632
00:32:54,368 --> 00:32:55,768
No.

633
00:32:55,770 --> 00:32:58,137
No,
just that you married one.

634
00:33:00,140 --> 00:33:02,241
Well, see,
here's the deal.

635
00:33:02,243 --> 00:33:05,011
Now there are eight killers
out there

636
00:33:05,013 --> 00:33:08,013
that we have to deal with,
not just one.

637
00:33:08,015 --> 00:33:09,815
I don't think so.

638
00:33:09,817 --> 00:33:12,552
What? Why not?

639
00:33:12,554 --> 00:33:17,123
Brick used to say
the heart was key.

640
00:33:17,125 --> 00:33:20,293
That was the focus
of the sacrifice.

641
00:33:20,295 --> 00:33:24,564
Are you saying that if we stop
Brick's beating heart,

642
00:33:24,566 --> 00:33:26,365
then we could stop
the whole thing?

643
00:33:28,469 --> 00:33:33,172
Do you know where the person is
who has the heart?

644
00:33:33,174 --> 00:33:35,608
Do you know?

645
00:33:46,521 --> 00:33:47,553
Really?

646
00:33:47,555 --> 00:33:49,522
Our king daddy monster
is a stripper?

647
00:33:49,524 --> 00:33:53,159
We're pretty sure
this is gonna work, right?

648
00:33:53,161 --> 00:33:57,230
Well, as long as Eleanor knows
what she's talking about.

649
00:34:00,235 --> 00:34:02,035
You think Brick thought
maybe he'd burn to nothing

650
00:34:02,037 --> 00:34:03,170
when he crashed that car?

651
00:34:03,172 --> 00:34:06,540
Yeah, but he didn't,
which brings us here.

652
00:34:47,515 --> 00:34:50,150
Smell that?

653
00:34:50,152 --> 00:34:51,986
You're gross.

654
00:35:20,549 --> 00:35:24,686
Eleanor sent you,
right?

655
00:35:24,688 --> 00:35:27,889
I figured she'd probably break
and give me up.

656
00:35:27,891 --> 00:35:31,893
This won't end well for her,
of course.

657
00:35:31,895 --> 00:35:34,196
Not that it's gonna end well
for you.

658
00:35:37,733 --> 00:35:39,735
Oh, now, you don't think we're
gonna let you do that, do you?

659
00:35:39,737 --> 00:35:41,336
"We"?

660
00:35:48,945 --> 00:35:50,479
I'm the guy from Phoenix
you were looking for.

661
00:35:59,856 --> 00:36:01,656
Oh, you guys are stronger
than you look.

662
00:36:01,658 --> 00:36:04,659
Comes with the package.
Plus, I work out a lot.

663
00:36:08,130 --> 00:36:09,898
You can't imagine
who I was before.

664
00:36:09,900 --> 00:36:13,835
This shy, awkward little thing
from Georgia

665
00:36:13,837 --> 00:36:15,870
with a heart condition.

666
00:36:15,872 --> 00:36:17,939
Then I had the surgery.

667
00:36:19,276 --> 00:36:22,844
I became freaking
Xena: Warrior Princess.

668
00:36:25,349 --> 00:36:28,751
I couldn't dissect a frog
in high school.

669
00:36:28,753 --> 00:36:31,821
But sacrificing to Cacao?

670
00:36:31,823 --> 00:36:33,256
Better than sex.

671
00:36:35,160 --> 00:36:42,899
So, if I go real slow
and take my time and enjoy this,

672
00:36:42,901 --> 00:36:46,436
I can actually show you
your own beating heart

673
00:36:46,438 --> 00:36:48,705
before you die.

674
00:36:54,112 --> 00:36:55,812
Aah! Aah!

675
00:37:23,407 --> 00:37:25,609
Aah!

676
00:37:47,657 --> 00:37:49,657
Well, we better get going, uh...

677
00:37:50,013 --> 00:37:53,482
We just wanted you to know
that it really is over now.

678
00:37:53,484 --> 00:37:57,753
Well, it had to be,
one way or the other.

679
00:37:57,755 --> 00:38:02,525
I half thought you might fail
and Randa would come after me.

680
00:38:02,527 --> 00:38:06,395
Either way,
I'd finally be at peace.

681
00:38:09,067 --> 00:38:11,934
You take care of yourself,
Eleanor.

682
00:38:17,409 --> 00:38:19,943
Wow. Back in business.

683
00:38:19,945 --> 00:38:21,344
Got the win.

684
00:38:21,346 --> 00:38:24,347
Admit it --
feels good, huh?

685
00:38:24,349 --> 00:38:26,282
You know, I was thinking about
what Randa said about, uh,

686
00:38:26,284 --> 00:38:28,451
you know, what it feels like
to be a warrior.

687
00:38:28,453 --> 00:38:31,520
I get it, man, I do.

688
00:38:31,522 --> 00:38:35,024
I know.
I know you do.

689
00:38:35,026 --> 00:38:36,492
I don't.

690
00:38:36,494 --> 00:38:39,461
Not anymore.
Hell, maybe I never did.

691
00:38:39,463 --> 00:38:41,330
Come on, Sam, don't ruin
my buzz, would you?

692
00:38:41,332 --> 00:38:43,098
Dean, listen,
when this is over --

693
00:38:43,100 --> 00:38:46,635
when we close up shop
on Kevin and the tablet --

694
00:38:46,637 --> 00:38:48,771
I'm done.
I mean that.

695
00:38:48,773 --> 00:38:50,539
No, you don't.

696
00:38:50,541 --> 00:38:52,875
Dean,
the year that I took off,

697
00:38:52,877 --> 00:38:55,577
I had something
I've never had.

698
00:38:56,980 --> 00:38:58,280
A normal life.

699
00:38:58,282 --> 00:39:00,983
I mean, I got to see
what that felt like.

700
00:39:03,386 --> 00:39:06,122
I want that.

701
00:39:06,124 --> 00:39:08,024
I <i>had</i> that.

702
00:39:08,026 --> 00:39:13,195
I think that's just how you feel
right now.

703
00:39:19,969 --> 00:39:23,605
Amelia!
Amelia, this isn't funny.

704
00:39:25,074 --> 00:39:27,042
Amelia!

705
00:39:30,746 --> 00:39:32,880
Riot?

706
00:39:32,882 --> 00:39:34,148
Riot!

707
00:39:39,120 --> 00:39:40,821
Happy Birthday!

708
00:39:44,626 --> 00:39:46,127
What is this?

709
00:39:46,129 --> 00:39:49,631
You've never seen
a birthday cake before?

710
00:39:49,633 --> 00:39:51,767
Sit.

711
00:39:51,769 --> 00:39:55,004
Eat.

712
